<xa>偏教</xa>權教 Partial or
relative teaching; Tiantai regarded its own teachings the

complete, or final and all-embracing
teaching of the Buddha, while that of the

<xa>法相</xa>, 三論, etc., was partial and imperfect; in like manner, the three
schools, 藏,通

and 別, pitaka,intermediate, and separate, were partial and imperfect.



[343]

<xa>偏眞</xa>, 偏空, 單空The Hīnayāna doctrine of unreality, a one-sided dogma in contrast
with

the transcendental reality of Mahāyāna.

<xa>偏衫</xa>The monk's toga, or robe, thrown over one shoulder, some say the
